<BR><DIV CLASS="c4"><P CLASS="c5"><SPAN CLASS="c6">Cruz reverses course</SPAN></P>
</DIV>
<BR><DIV CLASS="c4"><P CLASS="c5"><SPAN CLASS="c7">BYLINE: </SPAN><SPAN CLASS="c2">Kevin Armstrong</SPAN></P>
</DIV>
<BR><DIV CLASS="c4"><P CLASS="c5"><SPAN CLASS="c7">SECTION: </SPAN><SPAN CLASS="c2">NEWS; Pg. 5</SPAN></P>
</DIV>
<BR><DIV CLASS="c4"><P CLASS="c5"><SPAN CLASS="c7">LENGTH: </SPAN><SPAN CLASS="c2">98 words</SPAN></P>
</DIV>
<BR><DIV CLASS="c4"><P CLASS="c8"><SPAN CLASS="c2">A DAY after suggesting George Zimmerman could not escape street justice after being acquitted in the fatal shooting of Trayvon Martin, Giants receiver Victor Cruz ran a reverse Sunday.</SPAN></P>
<P CLASS="c8"><SPAN CLASS="c2">Cruz apologized for a Twitter post in which he said &quot;Zimmerman doesn't last a year before the hood catches up to him.&quot; He quickly deleted it after backlash from followers Saturday night.</SPAN></P>
<P CLASS="c8"><SPAN CLASS="c2">&quot;I immediately realized my tweet was a mistake and I apologize, that's why I deleted it,&quot; he said in a series of Twitter messages. &quot;I believe conversation not confrontation leads to change and progress.&quot;</SPAN></P>
<P CLASS="c8"><SPAN CLASS="c2">Kevin Armstrong </SPAN></P>
</DIV>
